Aim
To write a program that demonstrates the use of constructors (default, parameterized, and copy constructor) and destructor in C++.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with data members.
Define a default constructor to initialize values.
Define a parameterized constructor to initialize values using arguments.
Define a copy constructor to copy values of another object.
Define a destructor to display a message when the object is destroyed.
Create objects using each type of constructor.
Display object values to verify constructor operations.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Sample {
    int x;

public:
    // Default constructor
    Sample() {
        x = 0;
        cout << "Default Constructor Called" << endl;
    }

    // Parameterized constructor
    Sample(int a) {
        x = a;
        cout << "Parameterized Constructor Called" << endl;
    }

    // Copy constructor
    Sample(const Sample &obj) {
        x = obj.x;
        cout << "Copy Constructor Called" << endl;
    }

    // Function to display value
    void display() {
        cout << "Value of x: " << x << endl;
    }

    // Destructor
    ~Sample() {
        cout << "Destructor Called for object with x = " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Calling default constructor
    Sample s1;
    s1.display();

    // Calling parameterized constructor
    Sample s2(50);
    s2.display();

    // Calling copy constructor
    Sample s3(s2);
    s3.display();

    return 0;
}

Output (Result)
Default Constructor Called
Value of x: 0

Parameterized Constructor Called
Value of x: 50

Copy Constructor Called
Value of x: 50

Destructor Called for object with x = 50
Destructor Called for object with x = 50
Destructor Called for object with x = 0


Result
Thus, the program successfully demonstrates
